'''Benito Antonio Martínez Ocasio''' (born March 10, 1994), known professionally as '''Bad Bunny''', is a Puerto Rican rapper and singer. His musical style is defined as [[Latin trap]] and [[reggaeton]].<ref name="Encyclopedia Britannica 1994">{{cite web | title=Bad Bunny - Biography, Albums, Songs, Music, & Facts | website=Encyclopedia Britannica | date=March 10, 1994 | url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Bad-Bunny-singer-and-songwriter | access-date=May 20, 2022}}</ref> He rose to prominence in 2016 with his song "Diles", which led to a deal with Hear This Music. He continued gaining traction with songs such as "[[Soy Peor]]" and collaborations with [[Farruko]], [[Karol G]], [[Ozuna]], [[J Balvin]], and more during the next few years.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-05-24 |title=The World's Newest Superhero: Bad Bunny |language=en-US |work=GQ |url=https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-june-cover-profile |access-date=2022-09-11}}</ref>

His major breakthrough came in 2018 with his feature on [[Cardi B]]'s number-one song "[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]" alongside [[J Balvin]],<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=2018-07-02 |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> and his top-ten song "[[Mia (Bad Bunny song)|Mia]]" featuring [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]. His debut album ''[[X 100pre]]'' was released in December 2018 by Rimas Entertainment, which peaked at number 11 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zellner |first=Xander |date=2019-01-03 |title=Bad Bunny Scores First No. 1 On Top Latin Albums Chart With Debut LP 'X 100PRE' |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-first-no-1-top-latin-albums-chart-x-100pre/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> He then released his collaborative album ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'' with J Balvin in June 2019, reaching number nine on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Coscarelli |first=Joe |date=2019-06-28 |title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, 'Oasis' |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html |access-date=2022-09-11 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bad Bunny's second album ''[[YHLQMDLG]]'' was released on February 29, 2020, and became the highest charting all-Spanish album, reaching number two on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Roiz |first=Jessica |date=2021-03-01 |title='YHLQMDLG' Celebrates 1 Year: Here Are 5 Ways Bad Bunny's Album Made History |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-album-anniversary-9533144/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> It was followed up with the compilation album ''[[Las que no iban a salir]]'' in May, which reached number seven on the chart.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny: LAS QUE NO IBAN A SALIR |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-las-que-no-iban-a-salir/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |website=Pitchfork |language=en-US}}</ref>

In November 2020, Bad Bunny released his fourth album ''[[El Último Tour Del Mundo]]'', combining his reggaeton and Latin trap sound with rock music.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny: El Último Tour del Mundo |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |website=Pitchfork |language=en-US}}</ref> The album became the first all-Spanish-language album to reach number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 and its lead single "[[Dakiti|Dákiti]]" debuted in the top ten on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In May 2022, his fifth album ''[[Un Verano Sin Ti]]'' released, which became his second number-one album and topped the [[Billboard Year-End|''Billboard'' 200 Year-End]] chart, while four of the album's singles peaked in the top ten on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Bustios |first=Pamela |date=2022-12-01 |title=Bad Bunny’s ‘Un Verano Sin Ti’ Is This Year’s Top Billboard 200 Album: The Year in Charts |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-top-billboard-200-album-year-charts-2022-1235176756/ |access-date=2022-12-01 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> ''Un Verano Sin Ti'' was the first Spanish-language album to earn a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Grein|first=Paul|date=November 15, 2022|title=Beyonce Ties All-Time Grammy Nominations Record|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/beyonce-2023-grammy-nominations-analysis-1235171262/|access-date=November 15, 2022|website=Billboard}}</ref>

Bad Bunny is credited with helping Spanish-language music achieve mainstream popularity in the worldwide market. In 2020, he became the first non-English language act to be [[Spotify]]'s [[List of most-streamed artists on Spotify#Most-streamed artists|most streamed artist of the year]] and achieved the same record again in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny Says His 'Mission' Wasn't Going Worldwide: I Didn't Create Music 'for the Gringo Audience' |url=https://people.com/music/bad-bunny-says-his-mission-wasnt-going-worldwide/ |access-date=2022-09-11 |website=Peoplemag |language=en}}</ref> He then had the biggest streaming year for any artist on Spotify in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Drake Congratulates Bad Bunny on Breaking Spotify Streaming Record: 'My Guy Is Moving Different' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/drake-congratulates-bad-bunny-all-time-record-biggest-streaming-year-spotify |access-date=2022-09-11 |website=Complex |language=en}}</ref> Bad Bunny has earned two [[Grammy Awards]], four [[Latin Grammy Awards]], eight [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], and thirteen [[Premios lo Nuestro]] awards. He was crowned Artist of the Year at the Apple Music Awards 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny is Apple Music's Artist of the Year for 2022 |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2022/11/bad-bunny-is-apple-musics-artist-of-the-year-for-2022/ |access-date=2022-11-09 |website=Apple Newsroom |language=en-US}}</ref> Bad Bunny has sold 5 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny album sales |url=https://bestsellingalbums.org/artist/1092 |website=Best Selling Albums |access-date=December 17, 2022}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Benito Antonio Martínez Ocasio was born on March 10, 1994, in the [[Almirante Sur]] barrio of [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico|Vega Baja]], [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vegabaja.gov.pr/bad-bunny-da-la-mano-en-almirante-sur/|title=Bad Bunny da la mano en su comunidad de Almirante Sur en Vega Baja|last=Avilez|first=Ana|date=September 16, 2017|work=2019 Municipio Autónomo de Vega Baja|access-date=June 28, 2018|language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531212950/http://www.vegabaja.gov.pr/bad-bunny-da-la-mano-en-almirante-sur/|archive-date=May 31, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> His father, Tito Martínez, was a truck driver, and his mother, Lysaurie Ocasio, is a retired schoolteacher.<ref name=twolatinas>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/two-latinas-created-rolling-stone-s-historic-bad-bunny-cover-n1208081|title= Two Latinas created Rolling Stone's historic Bad Bunny cover, a first for the magazine|work=[[NBC News]]|last=Acevedo|first=Nicole|date=May 15, 2020|access-date=May 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name="fader">{{cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/08/28/bad-bunny-cover-story-conejo-malo-interview|title=Cover Story: Bad Bunny|work=The Fader|date=August 28, 2018|access-date=November 26, 2019|last=Escobedo Shepard|first=Julianne}}</ref> His mother often listened to salsa, merengue, and ballads.<ref name="NPR 2019">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/03/681982377/how-bad-bunny-skipped-categories-and-skyrocketed-to-fame|title=How Bad Bunny Skipped Categories And Skyrocketed To Fame|work=NPR|last=Garsd|first=Jasmine|date=January 3, 2019|access-date=May 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name="NPR 2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2018/12/24/679179404/bad-bunny-en-espa-ol-el-nuevo-disco-y-sus-influencias|title=Bad Bunny En Español: El Nuevo Disco Y Sus Influencias|website=NPR.org}}</ref> He has two younger brothers, Bernie and Bysael.<ref name="fader"/> He's said, "I wasn't the kid who got involved in the streets. I liked to be at home with my family."<ref name=rscoverstory>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-cover-story-lockdown-puerto-rico-new-albums-996871/|title= Bad Bunny in Captivity|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 14, 2020|access-date=May 14, 2020}}</ref>

As a child, he attended church weekly with his devoutly [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] mother and sang in the church choir until age 13. After leaving the choir, he developed an interest in the artists he heard on the radio, particularly [[Daddy Yankee]] and [[Héctor Lavoe]].<ref name="fader"/> His stage name came from a time in which he was forced to wear a bunny costume and was angry about it.<ref name="NPR 2019"/>

Speaking about the Puerto Rican music industry, he stated, "I'm from Vega Baja, a small area that's not a metropolis like San Juan where the majority of the genre's artists have come from."<ref name="rolling stone">{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bad-bunny-latin-trap-concert-tour-w517474 |title=Bad Bunny: The Four-Billion-Stream Man Leading the Latin Trap Explosion |last=Light |first=Elias |date=April 2, 2018 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=June 28, 2018 |archive-date=June 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615190547/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bad-bunny-latin-trap-concert-tour-w517474 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

== Career ==

=== 2013–2017: Career beginnings ===
He started to write and create his own interpretations at the age of 14,<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=2020-05-14|title=Bad Bunny en Cautiverio|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-en-cautiverio-portada-junio-2020-999350/|access-date=2021-08-12|magazine=Rolling Stone|language=en-US}}</ref> until, in 2013, he began to publish his songs through SoundCloud, including "Get" in 2013, "Tentación" in 2014, "Just let me know" in 2015, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|last=CMTV|title=CMTV – Biografía de Bad Bunny|url=https://www.cmtv.com.ar/biografia/show.php?bnid=2498&banda=Bad_Bunny|access-date=2021-08-12|website=CMTV|language=es}}</ref> In 2016, his song "Diles" caught the attention of DJ Luian from [[SoundCloud]] who signed him to his record label, Hear this Music.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://peru21.pe/espectaculos/bad-bunny-ano-trabajaba-supermercado-385993|title=Bad Bunny: "Hace un año trabajaba en un supermercado"|date=November 27, 2017|work=Peru21|access-date=December 2, 2017|language=es|trans-title=Bad Bunny: "A year ago I was working in a supermarket"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/the-rise-of-bad-bunny-from-superstore-bagger-to-king-of-trap-music-exclusive-111455|title=The Rise of Bad Bunny: From Superstore Bagger to King of Trap Music (Exclusive) &#124; Entertainment Tonight|website=www.etonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://remezcla.com/features/music/bad-bunny-profile/|title=How Bad Bunny Became the Poster Boy of Trap en Español|work=Remezcla|access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=changingpop>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/partner/8480619/bad-bunny-how-a-latin-trap-artist-is-changing-the-world-of-pop|title= Bad Bunny: How a Latin Trap Artist Is Changing the World of Pop|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 18, 2018|access-date=May 13, 2020|last=Partridge|first=Kenneth}}</ref> His single "[[Soy Peor]]" reached number 19 on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=insidetrap>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-latin-trap-the-viral-sound-too-hot-for-radio-w501823|title=Inside Latin Trap, the Viral Sound Too Hot for American Radio|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=November 7, 2017|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=June 28, 2018|archive-date=September 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917170456/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-latin-trap-the-viral-sound-too-hot-for-radio-w501823|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bad Bunny's May 2017 collaboration with [[Karol G]], "[[Ahora Me Llama]]", reached number 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=hotlatinsongskg>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/karol-g/chart-history/htl/|title=Karol G – Hot Latin Songs Chart History|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=May 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=altlatinoahora>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2017/12/21/567803247/alt-latinos-favorites-the-songs-of-2017|title=Alt.Latino's Favorites: The Songs Of 2017|newspaper=NPR.org|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=December 21, 2017|access-date=May 5, 2020}}</ref> It was listed on "Alt.Latino's Favorites: The Songs Of 2017" as one of the best Latin songs of 2017.<ref name=altlatinoahora/>

In the summer of 2017, Bad Bunny signed a booking deal with Cardenas Marketing Network (CMN) for several Latin American countries.<ref name=":0">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7881994/bad-bunny-booking-deal-cmn|title=Bad Bunny Signs Booking Deal With CMN|magazine=Billboard|access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref> Starting in November 2017, Bad Bunny hosted [[Beats 1]]'s first Spanish-language show, ''Trap Kingz''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8022850/apple-music-beats-1-trap-kingz-bad-bunny-spanish|title=Apple Music's Beats 1 to Launch First Spanish-Language Show, 'Trap Kingz'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/bad-bunny/chart-history/htl/|title=Bad Bunny No Metes Cabra Chart History|magazine=Billboard|access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref> The remix of "[[Te Boté]]" with [[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]] and [[Nicky Jam]] reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/bad-bunny/chart-history/htl/ |title=Bad Bunny Chart History |magazine=Billboard |access-date=October 11, 2018}}</ref>

=== 2018–2019: ''X 100pre'', and ''Oasis'' ===
[[File:Bad Bunny concierto Ecuador.jpg|thumb|170px|Bad Bunny performing in Ecuador in September 2018]]
In May 2018, American rapper [[Cardi B]] released a collaboration with Bad Bunny and J Balvin, "[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]".<ref name=":4" /><ref name="I Like It">{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 2, 2018 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On October 11, 2018, Bad Bunny released "[[Mia (Bad Bunny song)|Mia]]" with [[Drake (musician)|Drake]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/bad-bunny-drake-mia|title=Bad Bunny and Drake Link for New Collab "MIA" |last=Cowen |first=Trace William |website=Complex |publisher=Rich Antoniello |access-date=October 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bad-bunny-drake-mia-video-736308/|title=Drake Tests His Spanish on New Bad Bunny Single 'Mia' |last=Leight |first=Elias |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=Jann Wenner |access-date=October 11, 2018|date=October 11, 2018 }}</ref> which reached number five on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8481033/kodak-black-zeze-bad-bunny-drake-mia-hot-100-top-5|title=Kodak Black's 'Zeze' & Bad Bunny & Drake's 'Mia' Launch in Billboard Hot 100's Top 5, Maroon 5 Lead For Fifth Week|magazine=Billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=October 22, 2018|access-date=October 23, 2018}}</ref>

Bad Bunny released his debut album ''[[X 100pre]]'' on December 24, 2018, on Christmas Eve 2018 on Rimas Entertainment.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8491328/bad-bunny-to-drop-debut-x100pre-album-on-christmas-eve-exclusive|title=Bad Bunny to Drop Debut 'X100PRE' Album on Christmas Eve: Exclusive Interview|magazine=Billboard|access-date=June 9, 2019|date=December 23, 2018}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], ''X 100pre'' received an average score of 84 based on five reviews.<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/x-100pre/bad-bunny|title=Metacritic Review|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name="TG">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/03/bad-bunny-x-100pre-review-off-kilter-debut-from-puerto-rican-powerhouse/|title=Bad Bunny: X 100PRE review – off-kilter debut from Puerto Rican powerhouse|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=January 3, 2019|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> Alexis Petridis of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised Bad Bunny's "off-kilter creativity".<ref name="TG"/>

In 2020, ''X 100pre'' was voted 447th in ''Rolling Stone'''s [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/rolling-stone-incluye-rosalia-y-bad-bunny-en-su-lista-de-500-mejores-discos|title=Revista Rolling Stone incluye a Rosalía y Bad Bunny en lista de 500 mejores discos|work=El Universal|date=September 23, 2020}}</ref>

On June 28, 2019, Bad Bunny released ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'', an eight-song collaborative album with J Balvin.<ref name=nytimesoasis>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, 'Oasis'
|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2019|access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> It peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=oasishot100>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/tlp/|title=J Balvin Chart History|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> and topped the ''Billboard'' US Latin Albums chart.<ref name=oasislatinalbums>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/lcm/|title=J Balvin US Latin Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, he joined protests against governor [[Ricardo Rosselló]].<ref name=europetourprotest>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-49013761|title= Bad Bunny stops tour to protest in Puerto Rico|work=BBC|date=July 17, 2019|access-date=May 14, 2020}}</ref> Bad Bunny and [[Residente]] released "{{lang|es|[[Afilando los cuchillos]]}}" ("Sharpening the knives") during the demonstrations.<ref name="Social Movement Soundtrack">{{cite news | title='Afilando Los Cuchillos' Soundtracks Puerto Rico's Social Movement in Real Time | website=NPR.org | date=July 25, 2019 | url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2019/07/25/744727518/afilando-los-cuchillos-soundtracks-puerto-rico-s-social-movement-in-real-time | access-date=July 26, 2019}}</ref>

=== 2020–2021: ''YHLQMDLG'', ''Las que no iban a salir'', and ''El Último Tour del Mundo'' ===
{{very long|section|date=August 2022}}
In February 2020, Bad Bunny was a guest performer at the [[Super Bowl LIV halftime show]], headlined by [[Shakira]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bajuder |first1=David |title=Jennifer Lopez, Shakira in joyful, exuberant Super Bowl LIV halftime show |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/02/02/jennifer-lopez-shakira-super-bowl-liv-halftime-show-review/ |newspaper=[[The Denver Post]] |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> Bad Bunny announced the album ''[[YHLQMDLG]]'' on February 27, 2020, during an appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' and stated that it would be released on [[February 29|Leap Day 2020]].<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-announces-new-album-and-performs-on-fallon-watch/|title=Bad Bunny Announces New Album and Performs on Fallon: Watch|last=Hussey|first=Allison|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> It was released on February 29, 2020.<ref name=dropsalbumcnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/entertainment/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-drop-trnd/index.html|title=Bad Bunny drops new album, 'YHLQMDLG'|last=Asmelash|first=Leah|work=CNN|date=February 29, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The album's title stands for "Yo Hago Lo Que Me Da La Gana" (Spanish for "I Do What I Want") and features collaborations with [[Daddy Yankee]], [[Yaviah]], [[Jowell & Randy]], [[Ñengo Flow]], among other artist.<ref name=dropsalbumcnn/><ref name=yhlqmdlgNPR>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/02/811180499/bad-bunny-review-yhlqmdlg-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-la-dificil|title=Bad Bunny Shows Us His Version Of Old-School|work=National Public Radio|last=Gomez Sarmiento|first=Isabella|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The album is an homage to the ''marquesinas'' (garage parties) Bad Bunny grew up attending, and features many nods to early/mid-2000s reggaeton.<ref name=yhlqmdlgNPR/> On the final song on the album, "<3", the artist announced his intention to retire after releasing one more album with the lyric "In nine months I'll release another, to retire calmly like [[Miguel Cotto]]", referencing the retirement of the Puerto Rican boxer.<ref name=yhlqmdlgNPR/> He noted that the stress of fame has had a negative impact on his mental health.<ref name=yhlqmdlgNPR/>

''YHLQMDLG'' debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming the highest-charting all-Spanish album ever on the chart at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9330424/lil-baby-first-no-1-album|title=Lil Baby Earns First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'My Turn'|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The album was met with critical acclaim, who praised the album's musical diversity.<ref name="MC">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/yhlqmdlg/bad-bunny|title=YHLQMDLG by Bad Bunny Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> "[[Vete]]" was released as the lead single of the album on November 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/bad-bunny-vete-music-video.html|title=Bad Bunny's Video for His New Breakup Song "Vete" Is a Series of Bad Bunny–Level Flexes|last=Curto|first=Justin|website=Vulture|date=November 21, 2019|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The album title was first mentioned during a sequence of the accompanying music video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talentomusical.net/confirmado-el-nuevo-album-de-bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg|title=Confirmado el nuevo álbum de Bad Bunny ''YHLQMDLG''|last=Alvelo|first=Joel|website=talentomusical.net|date=November 22, 2019|language=es|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8548839/que-tire-pa-lante-continues-dominate-latin-charts-daddy-yankee|title=Daddy Yankee's "Que Tire Pa Lante" Continues Its Latin Charts Domination|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 23, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The second single, "Ignorantes", with Panamanian singer [[Sech (singer)|Sech]] came out on February 14, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cmalone/2020/02/14/bad-bunny-previews-upcoming-album-with-sech-collab-ignorantes/|title=Bad Bunny Previews Upcoming Album With Sech Collab|last=Malone Méndez|first=Chris|website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name="auto1"/> In March 2020, Bad Bunny released the music video for "[[Yo Perreo Sola]]", in which the artist performs in [[Drag (clothing)|drag]].<ref name=dragmakeover>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-drag-transformation-yo-perreo-sola-video-974467/|title= Bad Bunny Gets a Full Drag Makeover in New 'Yo Perreo Sola' Video|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The final frame of the video denounces sexual harassment of women, and reads: ""If she doesn't want to dance with you, respect her, she twerks alone".<ref name=dragmakeover/> On the song and video, Bad Bunny stated "I wrote it from the perspective of a woman. I wanted a woman's voice to sing it–'yo perreo sola'–because it doesn't mean the same thing when a man sings it. But I do feel like that woman sometimes".<ref name=dragmakeover/> "Yo Perreo Sola" landed number one on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Latin Airplay]] chart, earning Bad Bunny his ninth No.1 on the chart in just over two years.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=June 3, 2020|title=Bad Bunny Nets Ninth No. 1 on Latin Airplay With 'Yo Perreo Sola'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9396040/bad-bunny-latin-airplay-yo-perreo-sola|access-date=June 4, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>

On April 4, 2020, he released the song "En Casita" on SoundCloud, which expressed solidarity towards others in quarantine due to [[COVID-19]] and featured vocals from his girlfriend, Gabriela Berlingeri.<ref name=rsencasita>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-quarantine-song-en-casita-gabriela-978522/|title=Bad Bunny Drops New Quarantine Song 'En Casita'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=April 4, 2020|access-date=May 6, 2020}}</ref> On May 10, 2020, Bad Bunny released his third solo studio album (fourth overall) ''[[Las que no iban a salir]]'', without previous announcements.<ref name=lqniasbillboard>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9374973/bad-bunny-drops-surprise-new-album-las-que-no-iban-a-salir-stream-it-here|title= Bad Bunny Drops Surprise New Album 'Las Que No Iban a Salir': Stream It Here|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Peters|first=Mitchell|date=May 10, 2020|access-date=May 14, 2020}}</ref> The album's title translates to "The Ones that Were Not Going to Come Out" and is primarily a compilation of previously unreleased or unfinished songs.<ref name=lqniashighdebut>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9376803/nav-kehlani-lil-durk-bad-bunny-aiming-for-high-debuts-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title= NAV, Kehlani, Lil Durk & Bad Bunny Aiming for High Debuts on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|date=May 12, 2020|access-date=May 14, 2020|last=Caulfield|first=Keith}}</ref> Songs from the album were played on an [[Instagram]] live stream that Bad Bunny made in late April. The album features collaborations with [[Don Omar]], [[Yandel]], [[Zion & Lennox]], [[Nicky Jam]], and [[Jhay Cortez]].<ref name=lqniasbillboard/> Discussing the album's surprise release, Bad Bunny explained, "There was no real meaning behind it. I just thought, 'Damn. What people need is entertainment'{{-"}}.<ref name=rscoverstory/> Bad Bunny had been filming his supporting role in ''[[Narcos: Mexico]]'' before filming was postponed due to the pandemic.<ref name=rscoverstory/> It premiered in November 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/narcos-mexico-final-season-trailer-netflix-1235028734/|title='Narcos: Mexico' Makes Way for the Next Generation in Final Season Trailer|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 11, 2021}}</ref>

In July 2020, he appeared on the first digital cover of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine as the first man to appear on the cover other than the magazine's founder, [[Hugh Hefner]]. The cover was shot by photographer Stillz in [[Miami|Miami, Florida]] and the magazine includes a feature article entitled "Bad Bunny is Not Playing God."<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|first=Karina |last=Tsui|title=Bad Bunny makes Playboy history with new cover|url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-playboy-magazine/index.html|date=July 8, 2020|access-date=July 9, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> He also received the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP Latin]] award for Songwriter of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ascap.com/news-events/awards/2020/latin-awards |title=El Premio ASCAP 2020 |website=ASCAP |access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> The following month, his song "Pero Ya No" appeared in an advertisement for politician [[Joe Biden]]'s [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|2020 United States presidential election campaign]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Exposito|first1=Suzy|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-alejandro-fernandez-biden-campaign-ads-1050846/|title=Hear Bad Bunny, Alejandro Fernandez in New Biden Campaign Ads|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 28, 2020|access-date=August 30, 2020}}</ref> On September 20, 2020, Bad Bunny performed a surprise, live (via his YouTube channel and [[Uforia Audio Network|Uforia]]), free concert from atop a flatbed truck that looked like a subway car going through the streets of New York and ended at Harlem Hospital. With a motorcade including police and vehicles flashing their lights, the subway car with Bad Bunny on the top drove through [[The Bronx]] and [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/bad-bunny-performs-live-concert-from-flatbed-truck-driving-through-nyc/2627029/|title=Bad Bunny Performs Live Concert From Flatbed Truck Driving Through NYC|website=Nbcnewyork.com|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | last=Shaffer | first=Claire | title=Bad Bunny to Hold Exclusive Livestream Concert on Uforia | magazine=Rolling Stone | date=September 14, 2020 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-uforia-livestream-concert-1059443/ | access-date=September 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Bad Bunny energizes New York with surprise mobile concert | website=USA TODAY | date=September 21, 2020 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/entertainment/2020/09/21/bad-bunny-energizes-new-york-surprise-mobile-concert/5859990002/ | access-date=September 22, 2020}}</ref> In October 2020, Bad Bunny released the single "[[Dakiti]]", with [[Jhay Cortez]], which topped the [[Billboard Global 200|''Billboard'' Global 200]] and reached number five on the US Hot 100. The song is included on his third studio album, ''[[El Último Tour Del Mundo]]'', which was released on November 27, 2020, and was described as a personal and ambitious record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/11/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo|title=Bad Bunny Shares New Album 'El Último Tour Del Mundo'|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Cowen|first=Trace William|date=November 27, 2020|access-date=November 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name="Caulfield">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9495004/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-billboard-200-number-one|title=Bad Bunny's 'El Ultimo Tour del Mundo' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart, Is First All-Spanish No. 1 Album|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=December 6, 2020|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> It became the first all-Spanish language album to reach number one on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name="Caulfield"/>

Bad Bunny and ''YHLQMDLG'' respectively became [[Spotify]]'s most-streamed artist and album globally of 2020.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9491650/bad-bunny-spotify-wrapped|title=Bad Bunny Is Spotify's Most-Streamed Artist of 2020|magazine=Billboard|author=Aniftos, Rania|date=December 2020}}</ref> It marked the first time a non-English language music artist topped the year-end list,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9491694/bad-bunny-spotify-most-streamed-artist-2020|title=Many Billions: Bad Bunny Is Spotify's Most-Streamed Artist of 2020|magazine=Billboard|date=December 2020}}</ref> with a ''[[The Guardian]]'' article considering him "the world's biggest pop star" for his streaming numbers.<ref name="the guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/dec/04/how-did-bad-bunny-become-the-worlds-biggest-pop-star|title=How did Bad Bunny become the world's biggest pop star?|work=The Guardian|date=December 4, 2020}}</ref> The album received the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop or Urban Album]] at the [[63rd Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-wins-best-latin-pop-or-urban-album-at-2021-grammys/|title = Bad Bunny Wins Best Latin Pop or Urban Album at 2021 Grammys|website = [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date = March 15, 2021}}</ref> On February 20, 2021, Bad Bunny performed "[[La Noche de Anoche]]" with [[Rosalía (singer)|Rosalía]] and "Te Deseo Lo Mejor" on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', hosted by [[Regé-Jean Page]], as well as appearing in the pre-recorded musical sketches "Loco" and "Sea Shanty".<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Hoffman|first=Jordan|title=Rosalía and Bad Bunny Smolder in 'Saturday Night Live' Appearance|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2021/02/rosalia-and-bad-bunny-smolder-in-saturday-night-live-appearance|access-date=February 26, 2021|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=February 21, 2021|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-bad-bunny-sing-with-rosalia-appear-in-sea-shanty-sketch-on-snl-1130929/|title = See Bad Bunny Sing with Rosalía, Appear in Sea Shanty Sketch on 'SNL'|magazine = [[Rolling Stone]]|date = February 21, 2021}}</ref> On the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, Bad Bunny's next single "[[Yonaguni (song)|Yonaguni]]" became his fourth top 10 entry and first with no accompanying acts.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9586789/bts-butter-number-one-third-week-hot-100|title=BTS' 'Butter' Sticks at No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Bad Bunny's' 'Yonaguni' Debuts at No. 10|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=June 14, 2021|access-date=June 15, 2021}}</ref> Bad Bunny was cast in an upcoming [[David Leitch]]-directed film starring [[Brad Pitt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2021/film/news/bullet-train-first-look-brad-pitt-bad-bunny-1235047141/|title=Brad Pitt, Bad Bunny Slap Each Other Around|work=Variety|date=August 24, 2021}}</ref>

In July 2021, it was announced that Bad Bunny co-wrote and co-produced the fifth album of Puerto Rican [[Latin pop]] artist [[Tommy Torres]] titled ''[[El Playlist de Anoche]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Griselda|first=Flores|title=Bad Bunny Goes Producer: Latin's Hottest Star Gives Tommy Torres 'Rock Star Attitude'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9604462/bad-bunny-tommy-torres-producers-now-digital-cover-interview|access-date=2021-10-24|magazine=Billboard|date=July 22, 2021|language=en}}</ref> Bad Bunny won the most awards at the [[2021 Billboard Latin Music Awards|2021 ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] with ten, including the category Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9636054/billboard-latin-music-awards-2021-bad-bunny-surprises|title=All the Times Bad Bunny Surprised Us at the 2021 Billboard Latin Music Awards|magazine=Billboard|author=Roiz, Jessica|date=September 24, 2021}}</ref> In the following months, he was featured on [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]]'s single "[[Volví]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-aventura-volvi-breakdown-music-video/|title=Aventura and Bad Bunny Close Out The Summer (of Touching Again) With "Volvi"|work=[[Remezcla]]|date=August 3, 2021}}</ref> and released "Lo Siento BB:/" with [[Tainy]] and [[Julieta Venegas]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9640709/tainy-bad-bunny-julieta-venegas-lo-siento-bb-interview|title=How Tainy, Bad Bunny & Julieta Venegas Teamed Up For 'Lo Siento BB:/'|magazine=Billboard|author=Flores, Griselda|date=October 5, 2021}}</ref> In September 2021, he appeared on the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Roiz |first1=Jessica |title=Bad Bunny Named One of Time's 100 Most Influential People of 2021: 'He's an Artist, Period' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9630351/bad-bunny-time-100-most-influential-people-2021-j-balvin-essay/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=November 13, 2021 |language=en |date=September 15, 2021}}</ref> Bad Bunny's 2022 concert tour, El Último Tour del Mundo, is scheduled to visit the US and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/musica/el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-2022-la-gira-de-bad-bunny-que-lo-llevara-a-recorrer-estados-unidos-y-canada-nota/|title=El último Tour del Mundo 2022, la gira de Bad Bunny que lo llevará a recorrer Estados Unidos y Canadá|work=El Universo|date=April 12, 2021|language=Spanish}}</ref> He won [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Urban Music Album|Best Urban Music Album]] and [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rap/Hip Hop Song|Best Rap/Hip Hop Song]] at the [[22nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/files/22nd_annual_latin_grammy_awards_nominations_2021_09_28.pdf|title=THE LATIN ACADEMY OF RECORDING ARTS & SCIENCES, INC. 22nd Annual Latin GRAMMY Awards®|website=[[Latin Recording Academy]]|date=September 28, 2021|accessdate=September 28, 2021|archive-date=September 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210928191647/https://www.latingrammy.com/files/22nd_annual_latin_grammy_awards_nominations_2021_09_28.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''El Último Tour Del Mundo'' won [[Grammy Award for Best Música Urbana Album|Best Música Urbana Album]] at the [[64th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2022-grammys-complete-winners-nominees-nominations-list|title=2022 GRAMMYs Awards Show: Complete Nominations List|website=Grammys.com|date=November 23, 2021|accessdate=November 23, 2021}}</ref> In December 2021, it was announced that Bad Bunny became Spotify's most-streamed artist of the year globally, for a second year in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/dec/01/bad-bunny-most-streamed-artist-on-spotify-for-second-year-running|title=Bad Bunny most-streamed artist on Spotify for second year running|work=The Guardian|date=December 2021}}</ref>

=== 2022: ''Un Verano Sin Ti'' ===
In January 2022, Bad Bunny was featured in Vogue Magazine for the second time modeling the current season's best bags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny Models The Season's Best Bags |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/bad-bunny-bags |website=Vogue |date=19 January 2022}}</ref> In April 2022, [[Sony Pictures]] announced Bad Bunny as the lead for ''El Muerto'', a film set in [[Sony's Spider-Man Universe]]. ''El Muerto'' is set to be released on January 12, 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Donnelly |first=Matt |date=2022-04-26 |title=Bad Bunny Unveiled as New Marvel Hero 'El Muerto' for Sony Pictures |url=https://variety.com/2022/film/news/el-muerto-marvel-sony-1235240517/ |access-date=2022-04-27 |website=Variety |language=en-US}}</ref> On May 6, 2022, Bad Bunny released his fourth (fifth overall) studio album ''[[Un Verano Sin Ti]]'' which it became commercially successful as it debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and stood there for thirteen non-consecutive weeks.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-billboard-200-chart-debut-1235071183/|title=Bad Bunny's 'Un Verano Sin Ti' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|magazine=Billboard|date=May 15, 2022|access-date=July 15, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-billboard-200-chart-number-one-thirteen-weeks-un-verano-sin-ti-1235153095/|title=Bad Bunny's 'Un Verano Sin Ti' Ties for Most Weeks at No. 1 in Last 10 Years on Billboard 200|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 9, 2022|access-date=October 10, 2022}}</ref>

Bad Bunny began his fourth concert tour [[World's Hottest Tour]] on August 5, 2022, set to visit fourteen countries of the American continent.<ref name="Tour">{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/latinpower/musica/2022/01/24/worlds-hottest-tour-bad-bunny-confirmo-su-gira-por-america-latina-y-tocara-en-mas-de-10-ciudades/|title=World's Hottest Tour: Bad Bunny confirmó su gira por América Latina y tocará en más de 10 ciudades|website=Infobae|language=es|access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> On October 4, 2022, the tour became the highest-grossing tour by a Latin artist in history, earning US$232.5 million at the time.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last1=Frankenberg |first1=Eric |date=2022-10-04 |title=Bad Bunny Enters the Record Books With World's Hottest Tour |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-worlds-hottest-tour-sets-records/ |access-date=2022-10-04 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> Bad Bunny received the most nominations (eight) for the 2022 American Music Awards, including his first for artist of the year.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Bad Bunny Leads the 2022 American Music Awards Nominations |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bad-bunny-leads-the-2022-american-music-awards-nominations-billboard-news/|date=October 13, 2022|access-date=October 13, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

== Artistry ==

=== Musical and lyrical style ===
