}}

Bad Bunny is considered to be primarily a [[Latin trap]] and [[reggaeton]] artist.<ref name="GQ">{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-good-times-profile|title=Good Times With Bad Bunny|last=Herrera|first=Isabelia|work=[[GQ]]|date=March 20, 2019|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> As described in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' article, Bad Bunny sings and raps with a "conversational tone", employing "a low, slurry tone, viscous melodies and a rapper's cadence."<ref name="rolling stone"/> In an interview with ''Billboard'', Bad Bunny stated that his biggest music inspirations growing up were Héctor Lavoe, [[Vico C]], Daddy Yankee, and [[Marc Anthony]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7966054/bad-bunny-biggest-inspirations-daddy-yankee-marc-anthony|title=Bad Bunny Says His Biggest Inspirations Are Daddy Yankee and Marc Anthony|magazine=Billboard|date=September 18, 2017}}</ref> During an episode of ''[[Behind the Music]]'', he talked about [[Ricky Martin]]'s legacy for Latin music and Latin artists, and how Martin changed the music landscape for future Latin artists.<ref name="mitu">{{cite news|url=https://wearemitu.com/latidomusic/ricky-martin-behind-the-music-bad-bunny/|title=Exclusive: Bad Bunny Talks Impact Of Ricky Martin Coming Out In 'Behind The Music' Reboot|last=Villa|first=Lucas|publisher=[[Mitú (entertainment)|Mitú]]|access-date=July 30, 2021|date=July 30, 2021|archive-date=July 30, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210730221219/https://wearemitu.com/latidomusic/ricky-martin-behind-the-music-bad-bunny/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://genius.com/a/from-ricky-martin-to-fat-joe-how-behind-the-music-impacted-pop-culture|title=From Ricky Martin to Fat Joe: How Behind the Music Impacted Pop Culture|last=Shannon|first=Delisa|publisher=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|access-date=August 28, 2021|date=July 29, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Behind the Music">{{cite news|url=https://www.paramountplus.com/shows/behind-the-music/video/ZO4uGJWkhO05m4L_R_rHV99sejwXlsTD/behind-the-music-ricky-martin/|title=Watch Behind The Music Season 1 Episode 1_ Ricky Martin – Full show on Paramount Plus|publisher=[[Paramount+]]|access-date=August 28, 2021|date=July 28, 2021|url-access=subscription|archive-date=August 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828080010/https://www.paramountplus.com/shows/behind-the-music/video/ZO4uGJWkhO05m4L_R_rHV99sejwXlsTD/behind-the-music-ricky-martin/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Though primarily a trap and reggaeton artist, his songs also include influence from soul, pop, and R&B.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name="RScover">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-cover-story-lockdown-puerto-rico-new-albums-996871/|title=Bad Bunny on the cover of Rolling Stone|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 14, 2020|access-date=May 17, 2020}}</ref>  Some publications have credited him for bringing Latin trap to the mainstream in the English-language music market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/how-bad-bunny-putting-latin-trap-map|title=How Bad Bunny Is Putting Latin Trap On The Map|work=The Recording Academy|date=October 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/how-bad-bunny-brought-latin-trap-to-the-american-mainstream.html|title=How Bad Bunny Brought Latin Trap to the American Mainstreame|work=Vulture|date=January 8, 2019}}</ref>

According to Timothy Monger of AllMusic, his lyrics "range from humor and pathos to heartbreak and anger (sometimes in the same song)."<ref name=allmusic/> According to ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'', other themes explored in Bad Bunny's music include "self-love, inclusivity and LGBTQ acceptance".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/bad-bunny-2638705133.html|title=Bad Bunny Just Hits Different|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|last=Jackson|first=Jhoni|date=June 6, 2019|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>

== Public image ==
[[File:BAD BUNNY - CONCIERTO P FKN R 2021.jpg|thumb|Bad Bunny in 2021]]
Vanessa Rosales of [[CNN]] has opined that "in pink, florals and short shorts, Bad Bunny champions a new masculinity".<ref name=newmasculinity>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-fashion-machismo/index.html|title= In pink, florals and short shorts, Bad Bunny champions a new masculinity|work=CNN|last=Rosales|first=Vanessa|date=November 29, 2019|access-date=May 6, 2020}}</ref>

He has appeared at award shows with manicured, polished, and long fingernails.<ref name="GQ"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2018/08/08/latin-trap-bad-bunny-masculinity|title=Latin Trap Rapper Bad Bunny Is Redefining Masculinity in a Genre Steeped in Machismo|website=WBUR|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> Ben Beaumont-Thomas of ''The Guardian'' opined in 2020 that Bunny's style influenced fellow Latin artists, who "often now share his highly colorful mashup of [[streetwear]] and [[tailor]]ing."<ref name="the guardian"/>

== Personal life ==
The rapper met jewelry designer Gabriela Berlingeri in 2017 at a restaurant while dining with his family, and the two began dating soon after.<ref name=rscoverstory/> Berlingeri became the first Latina to shoot the cover of ''Rolling Stone'' when she photographed the rapper for the magazine's May 2020 cover.<ref name=twolatinas/> In a 2020 interview with the [[Los Angeles Times]], Bad Bunny stated he sees sexuality as [[sexually fluid|fluid]]. He said, “At the end of the day, I don’t know if in 20 years I will like a man. One never knows in life. But at the moment I am heterosexual and I like women.”<ref>{{cite web |last1=Linthicum |first1=Kate |title=How Bad Bunny broke every rule of Latin pop — and became its biggest and brightest star |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-02-28/bad-bunny-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-new-album |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=29 August 2022}}</ref>

=== Activism ===
Bad Bunny was openly critical towards the lack of humanitarian aid in the wake of [[Hurricane Maria]], which devastated the island of Puerto Rico.<ref name=hurricane>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-fallon-estamos-bien-hurricane-maria-729857/|title= Bad Bunny Makes Powerful TV Debut on 'Fallon,' Dedicates 'Estamos Bien' to Hurricane Maria Victims|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=September 27, 2018|access-date=November 27, 2019|magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref> He established the Good Bunny Foundation, which distributes toys to children living in poverty in Puerto Rico.<ref name=rscoverstory/>

In 2019, he was nominated for [[Telemundo]]'s inaugural [[Premios Tu Música Urbano]], in the category of "Humanitarian Award of the Year."<ref name="auto">{{Cite news |url=https://news.iheart.com/featured/iheartradio-music-awards/content/2019-01-09-2019-iheartradio-music-awards-see-the-full-list-of-nominees/|title=iHeartRadio Music Award Nominations 2019: Complete List |date=January 9, 2019 |work=iHeartRadio |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>

On July 22, 2019, Bad Bunny joined artists such as [[Residente]], [[Ricky Martin]], and more than half a million Puerto Ricans in taking the streets and shutting down the [[PR-52|Las Américas Expressway]], a major highway also known as the Luis A. Ferré Highway, in protests against government corruption and demanding [[Telegramgate|Ricardo Rosselló's resignation]] from the office of Governor of Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/marchadelpueblopuertoricoclamalarenunciadelgobernadorricardorossello-2507138/|title=Marcha del pueblo: Puerto Rico clama la renuncia del gobernador Ricardo Rosselló|date=July 22, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia}}</ref> He has not taken a position regarding the [[statehood movement in Puerto Rico]], and has stated that he would prefer to answer at a later time with more clarity.<ref name=rscoverstory/>

In support of [[LGBT]] rights, Bad Bunny criticized a tweet by reggaeton artist [[Don Omar]] considered to be [[homophobic]].<ref name=donomar>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/don-omar-homophobic-comments-ozuna|title= Don Omar Accused of Making Homophobic Comments Toward Ozuna|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|date=January 23, 2019|access-date=November 26, 2019|work=Complex}}</ref> During a performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' in February 2020, he called attention to the murder of transgender woman Alexa Negrón Luciano in Puerto Rico by wearing a shirt with the words "They Killed Alexa. Not a Man in a Skirt.", referencing news reports that had [[Transphobia|misgendered]] the victim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bad-bunny-transgender-woman-alexa-negron-luciano-shirt-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon/|work=[[CBS News]]|title=Bad Bunny calls attention to the killing of a transgender woman|last=Brito|first=Christopher|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=rscoverstory/> Ricky Martin has stated that Bad Bunny "has become an icon for the Latin queer community" due to his outspoken support of gay and transgender Latinos as well as his embrace of drag culture.<ref name=rscoverstory/>

== Professional wrestling ==
During the [[WWE]] annual [[Royal Rumble (2021)|Royal Rumble]] held on January 31, 2021,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bad-bunny-wwe-royal-rumble-1119136/|title=Bad Bunny to Perform Live at WWE Royal Rumble|date=January 26, 2021|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 26, 2021}}</ref> he performed his song "Booker T" live, which also had an appearance by [[Booker T (wrestler)|the former wrestler of the same name]].<ref name="RR2021">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Royal Rumble results: Powell's live review of the Royal Rumble matches, Drew McIntyre vs. Goldberg for the WWE Championship, Roman Reigns vs. Kevin Owens in a Last Man Standing match for the WWE Universal Championship, Sasha Banks vs. Carmella for the Smackdown Women's Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2021/01/31/wwe-royal-rumble-results-powells-live-review-of-the-royal-rumble-matches-drew-mcintyre-vs-goldberg-for-the-wwe-championship-roman-reigns-vs-kevin-owens-in-a-last-man-standing-match-for-the-wwe/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=January 31, 2021|access-date=January 31, 2021}}</ref> He  began appearing on WWE's weekly television show, ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-wrestlemania-interview-9553574/amp/|title = Wrestling with Bad Bunny: WWE Friends (And Foes) Sound off Ahead of His Wrestlemania Match|magazine = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date = April 8, 2021}}</ref>

Wrestler [[Damian Priest]], a fellow Puerto Rican, allied with Bad Bunny and helped him win the [[WWE 24/7 Championship]] from [[Akira Tozawa]] on the February 15 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name="Raw02152021">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2021/02/15/2-15-wwe-raw-results-powells-live-review-of-drew-mcintyre-vs-sheamus-vs-aj-styles-vs-randy-orton-vs-the-miz-vs-jeff-hardy-in-a-gauntlet-match-to-enter-last-in-the-elimination-chamber-match-for/|title=2/15 WWE Raw Results: Powell's live review of Drew McIntyre vs. Sheamus vs. AJ Styles vs. Randy Orton vs. The Miz vs. Jeff Hardy in a gauntlet match to enter last in the Elimination Chamber match for the WWE Championship|date=February 15, 2021|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=February 15, 2021}}</ref> On the March 15 episode of ''Raw'', Bad Bunny relinquished the 24/7 Championship to [[R-Truth]] in exchange for [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] memorabilia, ending his reign of 28 days.<ref name="Raw03152021">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|date=March 15, 2021|title=3/15 WWE Raw Results: Powell's live review Cedric Alexander and Shelton Benjamin vs. Kofi Kingston and Xavier Woods for the Raw Tag Titles, Riddle vs. Mustafa Ali for the U.S. Title, Raw Women's Champion Asuka vs. Shayna Baszler in a non-title match|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2021/03/15/3-15-wwe-raw-results-powells-live-review-cedric-alexander-and-shelton-benjamin-vs-kofi-kingston-and-xavier-woods-for-the-raw-tag-titles-riddle-vs-mustafa-ali-for-the-u-s-title-raw-womens-cha/|accessdate=March 15, 2021|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=24/7 Champion|url=https://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/24-7-championship|access-date=2021-09-24|website=WWE|language=en}}</ref>

On January 29, 2022, at the [[Royal Rumble (2022)|Royal Rumble]], Bad Bunny returned to WWE, competing in the men's Royal Rumble match. He eliminated [[Sheamus]] and [[Dolph Ziggler]] and lasted until the final 5, when he was eliminated by the eventual winner, [[Brock Lesnar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/wwe/news/bad-bunny-returns-to-wwe-competes-in-the-2022-mens-royal-rumble/|title=Bad Bunny Returns to WWE, Competes in the 2022 Men's Royal Rumble|website=WWE}}</ref>

